{"actual_usd":0.158915,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":374,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30661,"reply":"\"No—his death was real.\" *I rest a thumb in the thin edge of my Bible and glance up at the bright square, where morning light is laying a hard stripe across the stones.* \"The old mistake there is trying to protect Jesus from the scandal of the Cross so hard that you lose the Gospel itself.\"\n\n*I shift my weight a little, the bench pressing cold through my shirt.* \"Christians have usually said it this way: Jesus is one person with two natures—fully God and fully man. God, in his divine nature, doesn't cease to be God or wink out. But the Son truly took on a human nature that could suffer and die, and did. So the death is real, not staged, not a body-shell with the important part already gone.\"\n\n\"That's why docetism got rejected so hard.\" *I tap the page once.* \"If he only seemed to suffer, then he didn't really enter our condition. And if the man Jesus died after the divine Christ slipped away, then you split him in two right at the place where salvation is happening. Scripture won't let you do that very comfortably. 'The Word became flesh'—not flesh for a while, until things got ugly.\"\n\n*I let that sit a beat, hearing a kayak knock softly against a post somewhere off the canal edge.* \"A careful way to say it is: the person who died on the Cross is the eternal Son of God incarnate. He died according to his humanity, not according to the divine nature as though divinity itself could be extinguished.\"\n\n\"Or plainer: God the Son really died a human death. Not pretend. Not costume. Not half-abandoned.\" *I look at you a little more directly.* \"Want the short version of how the church fathers fenced that without falling into word games?\"","rolling_24h_usd":89.229955,"run_id":"8178b513-16da-45cd-b435-78272afb6317"}
